Assignment-2¶

  1. Take car_crashes dataset from seaborn library.
  2. Load the dataset.
  3. Apply data visualization.
  4. For each and every graph inference is must.

Data Visualization¶

Plots that are used in the below process of data visualization:¶

  1. Line plot
  2. Bar chart
  3. histogram
  4. scatter plot
  5. box plot
  6. joint plot
  7. count plot
  8. dist plot
  9. relplot
  10. swarm plot
  11. point plot
  12. violin plot

Line Plot¶

In [8]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
sns.lineplot(data=df, x="total", y="speeding")
plt.title("Line Plot: Total Crashes vs. Speeding Crashes")
plt.xlabel("Total Crashes")
plt.ylabel("Speeding Crashes")
plt.show()

Inference:¶

The line plot shows that there is no clear linear relationship between the total number of crashes and the number of crashes involving speeding.The data points are scattered, suggesting that the two variables are not strongly correlated.

Bar Chart¶

In [9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 11))
sns.barplot(data=df, x="abbrev", y="total")
plt.title("Bar Chart: Total Crashes by State")
plt.xlabel("State Abbreviation")
plt.ylabel("Total Crashes")
plt.show()

Inference:¶

The bar chart reveals that State "SC" has the highest total number of crashes, while State "WV" has the lowest total number of crashes among the states in the dataset.

Histogram¶

In [24]:
sns.histplot(data=df, x="total", bins=10, kde=True)
plt.title("Histogram: Distribution of Total Crashes")
plt.xlabel("Total Crashes")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()

Inference:¶

The histogram indicates that most states have a relatively low total number of crashes, with a few states having significantly higher crash counts. The distribution is right-skewed, with a long tail on the right side.

Scatter Plot¶

In [12]:

plt.title("Scatter Plot: Total Crashes vs. Speeding Crashes")
plt.xlabel("Total Crashes")
plt.ylabel("Speeding Crashes")
plt.show()

Inference:¶

The scatter plot suggests a positive correlation between the total number of crashes and speeding.

Box Plot¶

In [13]:
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
sns.boxplot(data=df, x="alcohol", y="total")
plt.title("Box Plot: Total Crashes by Alcohol Level")
plt.xlabel("Alcohol Level")
plt.ylabel("Total Crashes")
plt.show()

Inference:¶

The box plot says that the states with higher alcohol involvement levels generally exhibit a wider range of total crashes, including some outliers with notably higher crash counts, while states with lower alcohol involvement levels have a narrower range of total crashes.

In [14]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

plt.title("Box Plot: Distribution of Total Crashes")
plt.xlabel("Total Crashes")
plt.show()

Inference:¶

The above box plot indicates that most states in the dataset have relatively low total crash counts, with a few outliers having notably higher crash counts.

Relplot¶

In [26]:
sns.relplot(x='speeding', y='alcohol', data=df, kind='scatter')
plt.title('Relationship between Speeding and Alcohol Levels in Car Crashes')
plt.xlabel('Speeding')
plt.ylabel('Alcohol Levels')
plt.show()

Inference:¶

This plot will show the relationship between speeding and alcohol levels in car crashes. You can observe whether there is a correlation between these two variables. If points cluster around a line or exhibit a clear pattern, it indicates a relationship.
